Revival under the Great Leader
London — Waterloo is now two centuries past, and Napoleon's catastrophic defeat in that battle severely damaged France's self-esteem, to the extent that General de Gaulle omitted it from his account of French military history.
Despite this, if "greatness" refers to some personal trait, then both Napoleon and de Gaulle can be considered among the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a great leader.
In Marx's view, class struggles in France created an environment where figures like Napoleon, the grotesque mediocrity, became heroes.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not particularly outstanding as a general, and his victories should be attributed to the courage and dedication of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
Whether Napoleon was great or not, we must clarify whether greatness can be used to describe any leader.
If the answer is affirmative, then who can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believed that great leaders must meet two particularly important criteria.
First, can this leader recognize the historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck did so, as did his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; borrowing Bismarck’s memorable phrase, both heard the rustling of the "divine cloak."
Second, did this leader make significant decisions?
Of course, if a leader is forced to make a decision, he or she should neither be blamed for it nor credited for it.
Therefore, the key lies in whether the leader has the opportunity to weigh pros and cons and make the right decisions on behalf of the country.
de Gaulle should therefore be listed among any ranking of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he led France out of the post-World War II decline.
After regaining power in 1958, he again saved his country by suppressing two attempted coups, ending the Algerian War, and establishing the Fifth Republic constitution.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview, securing their place in the post-war global order.
In fact, the ultimate impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in establishing their respective countries' worldviews may have been overstated.
Their successors continue to view the world—and the role their own country plays—in terms of constraining rational debate and distorting decision-making many years later.
The result is that the leaders who followed in both countries were never able to achieve accomplishments that could match those of the two great leaders.
But there is one British prime minister who can match her: Margaret Thatcher, a highly controversial figure whom people either love or hate just as much.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was due to rebellious activities within her own cabinet and party.
But one does not need to please everyone to be a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics cannot deny her influence.
Besides being the first female prime minister of the United Kingdom and one of the earliest female prime ministers in other countries, Thatcher helped reverse Britain's economic decline.
Moreover, her offensive against powerful trade unions enhanced its manageability at a time when the country seemed to be sliding into turmoil and chaos.
Given this context, she certainly has the right to be considered a "great leader."
Similarly, though not without flaws, Deng Xiaoping of China also deserves to be considered a great leader.
In addition to aiding Mao in his evil deeds, Deng also played a decisive role in ordering the Tiananmen Square massacre in 1989.
But Deng also liberalized the market, setting China on a path of unprecedented development and prosperity that ultimately lifted hundreds of millions of Chinese out of poverty.
Many consider Singapore's founder and longtime prime minister Lee Kuan Yew to be a great leader, although he may have wished for a larger stage to showcase his talents.
In fact, the size of a country does not seem to affect one's potential to become a great leader.
I meant no slight when I said a small country like Luxembourg is unlikely to produce a great leader, especially given that the country's political atmosphere is generally not controversial.
America, with its vast expanse, is a place where great leaders can emerge.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — although not towering intellectual figures — demonstrated卓越的判断力 in establishing the post-war international order that supported decades of global peace.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possessed great talent — namely, the art of rhetoric and persuasion.
John F. Kennedy was certainly multifaceted.
He accomplished a great task: defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His talent for inspiring others was unparalleled; in fact, his assassination after death strengthened the traditions he had left behind.
In South Africa, no one has yet been called a great figure since Nelson Mandela's death, who embodied courage, authority, and gracious magnanimity.
In fact, he was the most charismatic leader I have ever met; the other two — former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former US Secretary of State Colin Powell — were either African or African Americans.
So today?
The only one qualified to call herself a great leader is the de facto leader of the European Union, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at the beginning, but rarely made wrong decisions when it came to making important ones.
Kohl established generous terms for German reunification; Merkel stood up against Putin during his invasion of Ukraine and took a tolerant approach to the migrant crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy were wrong.
Political leaders — those who exercise political power — can alter the course of events, for better or worse.
Merkel is the most obvious example today, as she pointed the way for Europe to address its high-stakes survival crises.
